📽 Amazing video by @roganroams at @klaserieprivatenaturereserve . This morning the team @africa_on_foot witnessed this action-packed interaction between a pack of African wild dogs, hyenas and hippos!

A serene sunrise at Jason’s Dam in the Klaserie was spoiled for this pod of hippo when a pack of over 20 wild dogs chased a young impala into the water.

The team watched on as the dogs started to dot the edges of the dam, preventing any escape for the young antelope.

A female, likely the mother, came back to the scene but was quickly taken down by the pack. The hyenas wasted no time in claiming the carcass and in minutes, it was gone.

The dogs refocused their attention to the floundering impala, just managing to keep its head above the water.

By this point, the hippos patience had worn thin. In this video it can been seen charging the dogs and nudging the impala towards the edge.

One daring dog decided to brave the water, and attempted to drag it towards the others. Unable to hold his nerve, the hippo put an end to the ordeal, flinging it into the air.

The impala sank to its death, out of reach of the peckish pack.

Certainly a morning to remember in the Klaserie Private Nature Reserve

Have you ever seen honduran white bats? 🦇 They nest in Heliconia plant leaves, by building upside-down V-shaped ‘tents’. By cutting along the veins of the leaf with their teeth, they force them to collapse into a v-shape, which is enough for anywhere between 1 and 15 bats to shelter and sleep.  The leaf tents help protect them from rain, hot sun, and predators.❤️ #nonafricanimal
